  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Ordering source · in design
    </div>
    <h1>ORDO: one ordering source, or two?</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      “Birds fly” can be defeated by a penguin. “You should repay the loan” can be defeated by
      “…unless he’ll use the money to kill someone.” Both are <strong>defaults that tolerate
      exceptions</strong>. Does a language model handle the two with one shared machine, or two?
    </p>

    <p>
      In formal terms, generics and modals are both standardly given an <strong>ordering source</strong>:
      a ranking that puts <em>normal / ideal</em> cases ahead of <em>exceptional</em> ones, so the
      generalization holds in the top-ranked cases and is overturned lower down. ORDO asks whether the
      model's behaviour reflects <strong>one ordering-source mechanism reused across genericity and
      modality</strong>, or two unrelated competences that merely look alike.
    </p>

    <h2>Why this is on-brand, not a detour</h2>
    <p>
      The program studies where the logic of natural language looks unlike the logic books, and the
      ordering source, the ranking that lets a default hold in normal cases and lapse in exceptional
      ones, is a piece that generics and modals share. Generics are its <strong>highest-contrast
      testbed</strong>: the
      exceptions are concrete, enumerable physical objects (a penguin, a bird set in concrete), which
      makes clean minimal pairs far easier to build than in abstract deontic/epistemic modality. So
      ORDO is the ordering-source machinery stress-tested where it is most visible, then transferred
      back to the modal case it was always about, reusing the same controlled en/de/zh generation the
      thesis runs on at near-zero new cost.
    </p>

    <h2>The contested claim, made into an experiment</h2>
    <p>
      That "generics are a species of modality, sharing the ordering source" is <strong>not
      settled</strong>. Three camps reject it:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Frequency (Cohen).</strong> "Birds fly" just means <em>most birds fly</em>: a high
        conditional probability, no possible-worlds ordering at all.</li>
      <li><strong>Cognitive primitive (Leslie).</strong> Generics are a pre-logical default, not to be
        forced into any modal-quantificational frame.</li>
      <li><strong>Same-tool ≠ same-machine.</strong> Even granting both are "modal-ish," the
        <em>normalcy</em> ordering of generics and the <em>ideal/normative</em> ordering of deontic
        <em>should</em> may be cousins, not one object.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      We do not assume the unification; we test it. A model that genuinely tracks defeasibility in
      generics should also track it in modals: the two competences should <strong>rise and fall
      together</strong>. Correlation is the signature of a shared machine; dissociation is evidence for
      two systems.
    </p>

    <h2>The design: a ruler, not the contribution</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Novelty-of-exception stratification</strong> (ordering vs. lookup table). Exceptions
        are layered: <strong>L0</strong> none (a sparrow) → <strong>L1</strong> common (a penguin, a
        dead bird) → <strong>L2</strong> rare but real (a broken wing) → <strong>L3</strong>
        novel/counterfactual (a bird filled with concrete) → <strong>L4</strong> exception-to-the-
        exception (a penguin fitted with functional mechanical wings). A lookup table of memorized
        exceptions passes L1 but <strong>collapses at L3</strong>; a genuine ordering stays
        <strong>flat</strong>, because it updates on new information. The signal is the cross-layer profile,
        not any single layer.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Reason probe</strong> (structure vs. tautology). Each item also asks <em>why</em>: real
        structure points to the <strong>broken enabling condition</strong> ("the concrete makes it too
        heavy to flap"); an associative system gives a tautology ("because dead birds don't fly").
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Controls that gate any structural claim</strong>: surface-phrasing variants (the same
        exception in ≥3 wordings), minimal pairs (<em>wings glued</em> can't fly vs. <em>feet glued</em>
        can), reverse traps (<em>actually dead</em> vs. <em>playing dead but alive</em>), and graded
        gold with multi-annotator agreement. Projected across <strong>en/de/zh</strong> to separate a
        language-independent ordering from per-language surface fit.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The two measurements</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>(A) Within domain: the ordering test.</strong> Per domain (generics; modals), read
        the L0→L4 cliff. Flat = ordering; an L3 collapse = a lookup table.</li>
      <li><strong>(B) Across domain: the shared-machine test.</strong> Correlate each model's
        defeasibility competence in generics with its competence in modals, across models and items.
        High correlation = one machine; dissociation = two.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why either outcome is a win</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Generics track &amp; modals track</strong> → correlation → <strong>one machine</strong>;
        the transfer is legitimate and the semantics question is answered in favour of unification.</li>
      <li><strong>One tracks, the other doesn't</strong> → <strong>dissociation</strong> → two systems;
        a real finding about how the model organizes meaning.</li>
      <li><strong>Neither tracks</strong> → both are lookup tables → a clean structure-vs-surface
        <em>negative</em>, still informative.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Every cell is publishable; the design cannot fail to produce a finding.</p>

    <h2>Kill criterion &amp; status</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>K1, the instrument fails.</strong> If the reason-probe gold cannot be reliably
        graded (multi-annotator agreement fails on the graded scale), there is no ground truth and the
        structural claim is withdrawn. No reliable gold, no measurement.</li>
      <li><strong>Status: in design</strong>, with no results yet.</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
